1 WHEREAS, The Maryland Youth Risk Behavior Survey showed that youth gambling
2 is increasing as 17.5% of high school students reported gambling in the last year compared
3 to two years ago when 15.3% reported gambling; and
4 WHEREAS, The Maryland Center of Excellence on Problem Gambling showed that
5 five of seven Maryland youth focus groups mentioned advertising as one of the biggest
6 reasons people gamble and Maryland youth are exposed to this general advertising on a
7 consistent basis; and
8 WHEREAS, The Maryland Youth Suicide Prevention School Program must continue
9 to adapt to the growing challenges facing youth suicide, especially with the increased
10 creation of conventional and online gambling in the State; and
11 WHEREAS, The Blueprint for Maryland’s Future works to help combat youth
12 suicide by recognizing student behavioral health issues and students experiencing trauma
13 or violence out of school and includes ways to provide these students with behavioral health
14 services; now, therefore,
15 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
16 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
17 Article – Education
18 7–501.
19 The General Assembly finds and declares that:
20 (1) A statewide Youth Suicide Prevention School Program is essential to
21 address the continuing problem of youth suicide throughout the State;
22 (2) The youth suicide problem often exists in combination with other
23 problems, including drug abuse [and], alcohol use, AND GAMBLING ADDICTION;
24 (3) A SUICIDE PREVENTION PROGRAM FOR YOUNG PEOPLE MUST
25 RECOGNIZE STUDENT BEHAVIORAL HEALTH ISSUES, RECOGNIZE STUDENTS
26 EXPERIENCING TRAUMA OR VIOLENCE OUT OF SCHOOL, AND REFER STUDENTS TO
27 BEHAVIORAL HEALTH SERVICES;
28 [(3)] (4) A suicide prevention program for young people must emphasize
29 a partnership between educational programs at the State and local levels and community
30 suicide prevention and crisis center agencies;
31 [(4)] (5) It is of vital importance that a statewide Youth Suicide
32 Prevention School Program be established with shared responsibility at both the State and

