1 (v) Enhance school climate and relationships between teachers,
2 counselors, and pupils; and
3 (vi) Further cooperative efforts of school personnel and community
4 youth suicide prevention program personnel;
5 (2) School or community based alternative programs outside of the
6 classroom, including:
7 (i) Positive peer group programs;
8 (ii) A 24–hour “hotline” telephone service, staffed by trained
9 professional counselors;
10 (iii) Programs to collect data on youth suicide attempts;
11 (iv) Intervention and follow–up;
12 (v) Mental health programs to promote mental health awareness
13 and encourage pupils to seek help as soon as it is needed; and
14 (vi) Parent education and training programs; and
15 (3) Teacher training programs.
16 (c) Any program established under this subtitle shall:
17 (1) Assist in increasing the awareness, among school personnel and
18 community leaders, of the incidence of teenage suicide;
19 (2) Train school personnel in individual and schoolwide strategies for
20 teenage suicide prevention;
21 (3) Develop and implement school–based teenage suicide prevention
22 programs and pilot projects;
23 (4) Develop and implement school–based pilot mental health programs and
24 peer–to–peer support to address the needs of students suffering from mental illness; and
25 (5) Through cooperative efforts, utilize community resources in the
26 development and implementation of teenage suicide prevention programs under this
27 subtitle.
28 (d) The Department may assist local school systems in implementing pilot
29 peer–to–peer mental health awareness programs.

